      \field{abstract}{To meet greenhouse gas neutrality goals by 2050, the demand for green hydrogen from water electrolysis is rising. Proton exchange membrane water electrolysis ({PEMWE}) offers high efficiency and operational flexibility for producing green hydrogen. However, the increasing number of {PEMWE} plants highlights the need for effective prognostic and health management ({PHM}) to ensure safety, extended lifetimes and reduction of operational costs. This publication addresses this need by first conducting a systematic review of existing degradation models for {PEMWE} components, cells, and stacks. The used methods, assumptions made, experimental validation, as well as the generalizability of the degradation models are evaluated. Based on these results we present a guideline for the development of robust {PHM} strategies for {PEMWE} stacks, considering factors such as data availability, health indicator setting, prognostic methods, and evaluation metrics. The guideline serves as a foundation for developing {PHM} approaches to reduce plant downtime, maintenance cost and enhance the longevity of {PEMWE} plants.}
